// 18-pinned-lifecycle — full birth/run/drain/dissolve on the
// pinned thread.
//
// In m27 (16-schedule-classes), pinned loci could declare ONLY
// run(). m28a lifts that: a pinned locus can now declare
// birth/run/drain/dissolve, and ALL FOUR run on the spawned
// pthread, in order, before the thread exits. The main thread
// joins at scope exit before destroying the pinned locus's
// arena.
//
// The whole sequence is deterministic because each method runs
// to completion before the next starts (single thread). The
// 30ms sleep in run() lets the main-thread println land
// between birth's print and run's print, proving the pinned
// thread really is parallel — main is doing other work while
// the pinned thread is in run().
//
// Per The Design / lotus, pinned and cooperative are bimodal
// projections of the same locus surface: same source,
// different runtime shape. m28a makes the pinned shape
// fully-featured for self-contained loci. Cross-thread bus
// (the thing that lets a pinned locus talk to the rest of the
// program) lands in m28b.

locus PinnedJob : schedule pinned {
    birth() {
        println("pinned.birth: setting up on the pinned thread");
    }
    run() {
        // Sleep so main can race ahead and print before us.
        std::time::sleep(30ms);
        println("pinned.run: doing work on the pinned thread");
    }
    drain() {
        println("pinned.drain: finishing pending work");
    }
    dissolve() {
        println("pinned.dissolve: tearing down on the pinned thread");
    }
}

fn main() {
    PinnedJob { };
    println("main: spawned PinnedJob; will join at scope exit");
}
